        <p>arXiv preprint (arXiv:2512.21199). Directly addresses the skepticism surrounding massive coaxial wiring footprints and their heat load. The authors demonstrate an optical-to-microwave (O2M) architecture using traveling-wave Brillouin transducers and uni-traveling-carrier (UTC) photodiodes at the 3.3 K stage, achieving 99.5% single-qubit gate fidelity while vastly reducing thermal conductivity to the mixing chamber.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/esserc62670.2024.10719526" target="_blank">Underwood et al. (2024) - "A 12.8 mW/channel cryogenic RF-AWG in 14nm FinFET for transmon qubit control"</a>
        <p>IEEE ESSERC. Confronts the heat dissipation bottleneck of integrating active control electronics inside the cryostat. By exploring sub-threshold 14nm FinFET device physics at deep cryogenic temperatures, this research demonstrates a functional RF arbitrary waveform generator dissipating only 12.8 mW per channel, crucial for scaling cryo-CMOS multiplexing without inducing thermal runaway.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.01031" target="_blank">Odeh et al. (2023) - "Non-Markovian dynamics of a superconducting qubit in a phononic bandgap"</a>
        <p>arXiv preprint (arXiv:2312.01031). Explores actionable research into phononic metamaterials to passively shield the quantum processor from mechanical vibrations (e.g., pulse-tube cooler noise). By engineering acoustic bandgaps, the periodic structural lattice suppresses phonon emission and coupling to lossy two-level systems (TLS defects), extending qubit relaxation times through structural isolation.</p>
      </li>
    </ReferenceList>
  </ContentSection>
